ed": true, "mention": "TH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 662, "end": 664}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GABAergic neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8948371410369873, "span": {"begin": 727, "end": 744}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7173"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TPO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.959946870803833, "span": {"begin": 835, "end": 838}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6528"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NIS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.980719268321991, "span": {"begin": 843, "end": 846}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GABAergic interneurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8648671507835388, "span": {"begin": 878, "end": 900}}], "text": "Thyroid hormone synthesis is responsible for physiological TH serum levels that subsequently correlate with TH brain concentrations. It has been shown that TH regulates function of different neuronal subtypes, including GABAergic neurons. TH increases glutamic acid decarboxylase (GAD) activity (responsible for GABA-synthesis) in neonatal brain, and GABA transaminase (responsible for GABA degradation) activity (Shulga and Rivera, 2013). GABAergic interneurons are remarkably diverse and complex in nature and they are believed to play a key role in numerous neurodevelopmental processes (Southwell et al., 2014). During the early cortical network development TH has been shown to regulate the morphology and function of the GABAergic neurons (Westerholz et al., 2010). It is well documented that decreased TH synthesis triggered by TPO and NIS inhibitors affects survival of GABAergic interneurons, as well as their morphology and function.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:46:54 +0000 2026"}